## The Last Step Before the Work Becomes Official

Day 42 closes out the Prepare phase of the NIST RMF — a phase that has spanned three weeks and produced more substantive work than I initially expected. When I started Day 21 with an overview of the full RMF, the Prepare step looked like administrative setup before the real work began. Having worked through it in detail, I understand now that it is foundational — and that organizations that skip it or rush through it end up doing the harder work later, often under worse circumstances.

System registration is the final Prepare step task. It is the act of formally recording OpenMRS in MyClinic's system inventory with the key attributes established over the past several weeks — the system categorization, the authorization boundary, the ownership assignments, the data sensitivity classification, and the compliance requirements. The registration record is what makes the system visible to organizational leadership, the security operations function, and future staff who need to understand what exists in the environment and who is responsible for it.

The absence of system registration is not a minor compliance gap. It is the condition that allows systems to become what security practitioners sometimes call shadow IT — systems that operate in the environment, handle sensitive data, and represent real risk, but that nobody is officially watching because nobody officially knows they are there.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-37 Task P-18 establishes system registration as the mechanism by which the organization maintains awareness of its information system portfolio. The registration feeds the enterprise system inventory — the authoritative list of systems the organization owns, operates, and is responsible for securing.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, system registration means producing the official registration record that captures everything established in the Prepare step in a structured, reference-able format. I worked through each field of the registration record, drawing on the detailed work from Days 21 through 41 rather than filling in generic placeholders.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clicked most clearly today is about the relationship between system registration and organizational memory.

Organizations change. Staff turn over. The IT administrator who built the OpenMRS deployment leaves. The ISSO who documented the security architecture moves to a different role. If the knowledge about what OpenMRS is, what data it holds, who is responsible for it, and what its security requirements are exists only in those individuals' heads — or in files on their personal laptops — that knowledge leaves when they do.

System registration is one of the mechanisms that institutionalizes that knowledge. The registration record is the starting point for a new ISSO who inherits responsibility for OpenMRS, for an auditor who needs to understand the system's security posture, for an incident responder who needs to quickly understand what the system does and what data is at risk, and for leadership making resource allocation decisions.

The registration record I produced today would tell a new team member everything they need to know to orient themselves: what the system is, why it exists, who owns it, what data it holds, what the compliance requirements are, how it is hosted, what systems it connects to, and where the detailed security documentation lives.

That is not bureaucracy. That is organizational resilience.

