## Why Each Field Matters

Working through each field of the registration record, I want to note the ones that are most consequential from a security perspective — not just from a documentation perspective.

**System Owner assignment** matters because without a named, accountable owner, security requirements get deferred indefinitely. The System Owner is the person who can approve resource expenditures for security controls and who is accountable when controls are not implemented.

**Categorization** matters because it drives the control baseline. A system registered as Moderate but actually operating with High-impact data will be selected for an inadequate set of controls. Getting the categorization right in the registration record ensures the rest of the security program is calibrated correctly.

**External connections** matter because every connection listed in the registration record is a risk pathway that needs governance. A connection not listed is a risk pathway with no governance.

**Change management requirements** matter because the registration record becomes stale the moment the system changes and the record is not updated. A registration record that accurately described the system at authorization time but does not reflect three years of subsequent changes is worse than useless — it creates false confidence that the documented security posture still applies.

