## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the context around the **2014 OPM breach** — which I covered on Days 11 and 22 from the role clarity and responsibility perspective — but want to revisit through the system inventory lens.

One of the findings from the OPM breach investigation was that OPM did not have a complete and accurate inventory of its information systems. The Government Accountability Office had flagged OPM's inadequate system inventory as a finding in prior audits. When the breach occurred, investigators found it difficult to determine the full scope of affected systems in part because the system inventory was incomplete.

The OPM case is an extreme example of what happens at the far end of the "invisible system" failure mode. When an organization does not know what systems it has, it cannot effectively monitor them, cannot respond to incidents affecting them, and cannot accurately assess the scope of a breach when one occurs. The system registration discipline that seems like administrative overhead in normal operations becomes critically important in the aftermath of an incident.

For MyClinic's OpenMRS deployment, the registration record produced today is the starting point of that institutional knowledge. It should be maintained, reviewed, and updated whenever the system changes — not filed and forgotten.

